COMBO GENERATION & PRICING STRATEGY LOGIC
AI Chief of Operations Agent - Conut Hackathon
This document outlines the step-by-step reasoning used by the AI Agent to generate, filter, and price combo recommendations using Market Basket Analysis (MBA) and historical pricing data.

STEP 1: Discovering the Pairings (Market Basket Analysis)
Before pricing anything, the agent looks at historical transaction data to find items that naturally "cluster" together. It uses three key metrics:

SUPPORT: How often does this combo happen overall? (e.g., 4.3% of all orders contain both Water and Chimney The One).

CONFIDENCE: If they buy Item A, what is the probability they buy Item B? (e.g., 66.7% of Water buyers also buy Chimney The One).

LIFT: Is this pairing a coincidence, or a true behavioral link? A Lift > 1.0 means the items are bought together more often than random chance. We only look at combos with a Lift > 1.2 to ensure the relationship is strong.

STEP 2: The Cannibalization Filter (Risk Assessment)
The biggest mistake in restaurant combos is discounting items that customers were already going to buy at full price. This destroys profit margins without driving new growth.

To prevent this, the Agent uses the "Confidence" metric as a Cannibalization Risk Indicator:

High Confidence (>60%): The customer is already buying these together naturally. (High Cannibalization Risk).

Low Confidence (<20%): Customers rarely pair these items. (Low Cannibalization Risk, High Growth Potential).

STEP 3: Dynamic Discount Sizing (Risk-Based Pricing)
Instead of applying a flat 15% discount to all combos, the Agent dynamically sizes the discount based on the risk profile established in Step 2:

If Risk is HIGH (Confidence >= 40%): The agent assigns a minimal 5% discount. This acts as a slight "nudge" or psychological reward without sacrificing existing revenue.

If Risk is MEDIUM (Confidence 20% - 39%): The agent assigns a 12% discount.

If Risk is LOW (Confidence < 20%): The agent assigns an aggressive 18% discount to incentivize a completely new purchasing behavior and increase basket size.

STEP 4: The Break-Even Target
Since we are giving a discount, we lose a small amount of revenue per transaction. The Agent calculates exactly how many MORE units must be sold to "break even" on that lost revenue.

Formula: Target Volume = Current Volume / (1 - Discount Percentage)

Example: If 12 people currently buy the "Triple Chocolate + The One" combo at full price, a 5% discount means we only need to sell 13 combos to make the exact same top-line revenue. Any sale after the 13th is pure revenue growth.

STEP 5: Handling "Zero-Price" Modifiers
The Agent cross-references the MBA data with cleaned_items_prices.json. It identifies anomalies—such as the "Strawberry + Classic Chimney" combo.

Finding: The Lift is massive (3.25x), but the Strawberry add-on has a unit price of 0.00 (it is a free modifier or pre-included topping).

Action: The Agent knows it cannot discount a $0 item. Instead of a price discount, the recommendation shifts to "Menu Engineering"—advising operations to make Strawberry a prominent 1-click add-on on the digital menu to improve user experience and speed up ordering.

SUMMARY OF THE AGENT'S BUSINESS RULES:
Only recommend combos with Lift > 1.2.

Never heavily discount items that customers already buy together (Confidence > 40%).

Always calculate the exact unit sales needed to break even before launching the promo.

Separate paid combos from free modifiers (Menu Engineering vs. Promotional Pricing).